c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"FGFR1 protein drives cholesterol uptake in tumors"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Study links lipid metabolism to treatment resistance"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"No immediate patient impact, but research opens new questions"}]]}]]}]}]
d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Prostate cancer’s ability to evade treatment has long puzzled oncologists. Now, researchers at ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://medicine.tamhsc.edu/","children":"Texas A&M Health"}]," have identified a mechanism that may explain part of the puzzle: a protein called ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"FGFR1"}]," that boosts cholesterol uptake in cancer cells. Published in ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://medicalxpress.com/","children":"MedicalXpress"}],", the study suggests this lipid-hungry behavior could help tumors not just grow, but resist therapies designed to starve them.\nThe finding centers on how prostate cancer cells hijack normal metabolic pathways. FGFR1, a receptor already known for its role in cell growth, appears to amplify the cells’ ability to absorb cholesterol—a nutrient tumors rely on for membrane stability and signaling. While the link between cholesterol and cancer isn’t new, this study pins a specific molecular player to the process.\nYet the work remains ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"preclinical"}],". The study examined cancer cell lines in controlled conditions, not human tumors in real time. As ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://vetmed.tamu.edu/","children":"Dr. Salman Hyder"}],", a co-author, notes in related research, such mechanisms often behave differently in the messy complexity of a living organism. The question isn’t whether FGFR1 matters—it’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"how much"}],", and under what conditions."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/how-cholesterol-fuels-prostate-cancerand-why-it-ma/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A molecular clue in prostate cancer progression—what the lab shows and what it doesn’t","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"A molecular clue in prostate cancer progression—what the lab shows and what it doesn’t"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["For patients, the implications are ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"not yet direct"}],". No clinical trials are testing FGFR1-cholesterol blockers for prostate cancer, and existing statins (common cholesterol drugs) haven’t shown consistent anti-cancer effects. The study’s value lies in its potential to refine future targets. If FGFR1’s role holds in human trials, it could explain why some tumors become resistant to androgen-deprivation therapy, a standard treatment that often fails over time.\nBut critical gaps remain. The study doesn’t clarify whether blocking FGFR1 would disrupt cholesterol uptake ",["$","em",null,{"children":"without"}]," harming healthy cells—a hurdle that’s doomed many metabolic cancer therapies. Nor does it address tumor heterogeneity: not all prostate cancers may rely equally on this pathway. As the ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cancer.gov/","children":"National Cancer Institute"}]," emphasizes, metabolic vulnerabilities in cancer are notoriously context-dependent.\nWhat’s next? The team hints at exploring FGFR1 inhibitors in combination with existing treatments, but that’s years away from clinical testing. For now, this is a ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"step in mapping the problem"}],", not solving it. The real test will be whether the lab’s clarity survives the transition to human biology—where cholesterol’s role is far more than just fuel for tumors."]}]]}]
